DOS TopSpeed Modula-2 with Objects    Release notes version 3.10
==================================    ==========================


This document contains information on the following:


        1.  DIFFERENCES FROM TOPSPEED VERSION 2.00
        2.  ERRATA
        3.  OBJECT-ORIENTED GRAPHICS INTERFACE
        4.  TOPSPEED EXTENSIONS
        5.  COMMON QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


1.  DIFFERENCES FROM TOPSPEED VERSION 2.00
==========================================

Major improvements and alterations to the TopSpeed Modula-2
compiler and code generator since the previous version include
the following:

■   More memory models are available, including an automatic code
    and data overlaying model.

■   TopSpeed Modula-2 now supports Microsoft Windows version 3.

■   Support for third-party libraries has been improved,
    particularly in the area of floating-point code generation
    (via the standard_float pragma). A large model stack-frame
    library is now supplied with TopSpeed Modula-2, which is
    likely to be of use when linking to third party libraries
    compiled for use with other vendors' C compilers.

■   TopSpeed Modula-2's object-oriented features have been
    enhanced, to support multiple inheritance and linking to C++
    classes. The syntax of class declarations have been changed;
    the supplied utility program NEWCLASS may be used to translate
    object-oriented source code designed for the previous release
    of TopSpeed Modula-2.



2.  ERRATA
==========

Reference manual p 17:

    The FIXREAL Real type should have the following numeric range:

        -2^63 to 2^63 -1

Reference manual p 18  paragraph 1:

    This paragraph should read as follows:

        Modula-2 has one predefined enumeration type defining
        truth values:

           TYPE
               BOOLEAN = (FALSE, TRUE);

Reference manual p 43:

    A type transfer function is considered well-behaved if the sizes
    of the transfer type and the value type are the same, or if a
    proper VAL conversion is performed. If the value type size is more
    than the transfer type size then the remaining last bytes of the
    value are ignored. If it is shorter, the last bytes of the resulting
    value are undefined.

Reference manual p 72:

    Line 18 of Example 1 should read as follows:

        RETURN(c1 IS classTwo)

