3.  OBJECT-ORIENTED GRAPHICS INTERFACE
======================================

Within the multi-language example programs is an object
orientated interface to the M2 graphics module.


4.  TOPSPEED EXTENSIONS
=======================

The following is a list of TopSpeed extensions to Modula-2 as
described in Niklaus Wirth's Programming in Modula-2, 3rd
edition.

Address constructor                     A := [S:O PT]

Based pointers                          SP : POINTER S TO T

Structured constants                    SC = A(C1,C2)

Concatenation of string constants       S = 'ST'+'RING'+CHR(13)

Type conversion of numeric types        I := INTEGER(CARD)

Standard types BYTE, SHORTINT, SHORTCARD, LONGCARD,
               LONGWORD, SHORTADDR

Standard constant NULLPROC

Object extensions, with CLASS, IS, VIRTUAL and SELF keywords.

Alias notation                             A ::= P

Compiler pragmas                           (*# ... *)

Conditional compilation                    (*% ... *)

Compiler directives (old style)            (*$ ... *)

SIZE and some other SYSTEM functions do not
have to be imported from SYSTEM

Function procedures may return any data type

Shift operators                             >> and <<

GOTO/LABEL                                  GOTO fail

SIZE may be applied to any expression or designated variable.

Identifiers imported in a definition module do not have to
be re-imported in the corresponding implementation module.

A module may refer to its own objects using qualified
reference.

Keyword INLINE allows specification of a procedure body
in a definition file.

Binary procedures can be defined to be a constant agregate.

VSIZE can find the size of a record (or object) type or
variable upto and including the specified field.

FieldOfs returns the offset of a field relative to the
start of a record (or object) variable or type.

A New function FieldOfs can be used to get the offsets of record
fields of record and objects, it works on variables and types.

Function procedure results may be dereferenced,
indexed or fields selected.

Procedures may be declared using a FORWARD declaration.

Procedure may be declared externally in another module
   PROCEDURE P; IN file;

Multiple-models mean that ADDRESSes and POINTERS can be 16 or
32 bits. FarADDRESS, NearADDRESS, FarADR and NearADR can
be used to specify these explicitly.

Procedure variables may be compared for equality.

Pragmas may specify various calling conventions/parameter
passing techniques.

Record fields may be packed by using a pragma.


5.  COMMON QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
================================

Q: How do I link to my own and other peoples C libraries?
A: If you want to interface to third party libraries you will
   have to use pragmas within the definition module to set C
   calling and naming conventions, and if necessary, to turn
   off register parameter passing. Of course if you use TopSpeed
   C to build your C library you can continue to take advantage
   of register parameter passing.

Q: How do I output to the printer using the library?
A: You can use the standard handle PrinterDevice defined in
   FIO.DEF which is pre-opened when your program starts. Then
   you can use all the FIO routines available, passing the
   handle as the first parameter  e.g:

   FIO.WrStr(FIO.PrinterDevice,'Hello'+CHR(13)+CHR(10)+CHR(12));

   An alternative is to use FIO.Open to open the printer device
   'LPT1' and use the handle returned in the same way.

Q: When using the C function printf from Modula-2, why does '\n'
   not get interpreted as a new line.
A: The \n and other escape characters prefixed by '\' are not
   actually processed by printf but are in fact part of the C
   language when defining constant strings. In TopSpeed Modula-2
   you can use string constant concatenation: e.g.
      printf("hello world"+CHR(13)+CHR(10));

Q: How can I use conditional compilation to include or exclude
   IMPORTs.
A: You can do this by having a boolean constant in a definition
   which then can be imported before the conditional compilation
   is needed.
   E.g.

       DEFINITION MODULE OSVER;
         CONST MSDOS = TRUE;  OS2 = NOT MSDOS;
       END OSVER.

   and in your implementation:

       FROM OSVER IMPORT MSDOS,OS2;
       ...
       (*%T MSDOS*)
       FROM SYSTEM IMPORT Seg,Ofs,Registers,CarryFlag,ZeroFlag;
       (*%E*)
       (*%T OS2*)
       IMPORT Dos,Kbd ;
       (*%E*)

Q: How do I export a procedure from a local module that is
   defined in the definition module:
A: As the definition of the procedure is already defined this
   procedure must be IMPORTed into the local module (not
   EXPORTed).
   E.g.
        DEFINITION MODULE test;
        PROCEDURE embedded;
        END test.

        IMPLEMENTATION MODULE test;
           MODULE local;
             IMPORT Embedded;
             PROCEDURE Embedded;
             BEGIN
             END Embedded;
           END local;
        END test.

   Note that using EXPORT instead of IMPORT is not supported.






